flowRoot.flowPara: Last versions always are incorporated in Sid (unstable).
Unstable: also known as SID, the neighbor who broke toys. Eternally unstable. This is an area for package stabilization. SID: Still in Development
Testing: stabilization area for the distribution as a whole. It's release as stable version which ready.
Stable: when a new version is released, it gets a codename. The first codename was Buzz, from Toy Story movie.

When a new version is released as stable, it immediately opens space in the testing, when starts a new cycle of distribution stabilization for a future release. All process follows a continuous and natural stream.
Experimental: area for bleeding edge version and experimentation. Is periodically used.
In general it is used to incorporate a great set of packages before going into unstable.
Debian Women: Seeks to balance and to diversify the Debian. Actively engaged with stakeholders and encourages women to become more involved with Debian.
Debian Mentors: Focused on helping new developers.
By DFSG, all changes made ​​in Debian are made available to upstream authors, benefiting Debian itself and other distributions.
On 1997-07-05, it was created the Debian Free Software Guideline.
Pure Blend: Debian Pure Blends provide a solution for special groups of target users with different skills and interests.
Derivatives: Debian provide a solid foundation to build a new custom distribution.
Distribution of Debian developers around the world
Debian Live: provides a framework to build official or customized Debian Live images to boot into Debian without requiring installation.

text.tspan: You inside of Debian Project (hard? No. Be a part!)

flowRoot.flowPara: Subscribe in the devel lists, talk with other developers and join a team with similar insterests in Debian Project.
do you wish to be a team member?
Read the technical documentation in the Developers' Corner, like New Maintainers' Guide, Debian Policy Manual or Debian Developer's Reference.
Found a bug? Send a patch!
Translate Debian web pages, manuals or package descriptions.
Write a manual, book or other materials that can help new users.
Adopt an orphaned package or start a packaging with a new software, alone or joing in a team.
Help new developers incoming in Debian Project as a mentor, a good place with experient people in packaging practices and that understand the Debian way.
Found a bug? Report it! You can use the webpage or "reportbug" tool.
Say "yes" at install time. It will help to choose packages for the first CD/DVD and to assess user-base for any package
Install, try and use in your computer.
Promote meetings, parties in the special dates of Debian, or presentations about Debian at IT events in your city or country.
